english:
  title: A Farewell Letter for Vice Editor-in-Chief Yu Upon His Return to Filial Service
  author: Kang Hee-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Hamyang, a county nestled among the many peaks of the Jirisan range, lies in the most remote and desolate corner of the land. When Kyŏngch'un spent the winter of Kapja in a cottage at Cheghye-ri, I was pursuing my studies and longed for a worthy scholar with whom to engage in discourse. The local academy had fallen into disrepair, and scarcely more than dozens came to study—all of them crude and narrow-minded folk. Twenty-one years later, in the summer of Kapoh, Kyŏngch'un entered mourning for his parents. That winter, he returned southward with his household. It was then that the exemplary Kim Jong-jik became magistrate of our county. The elders spoke with one voice: "Our magistrate honors learning and culture; learning and culture flourish greatly." Scholars from neighboring counties came bearing provisions to study, numbering more than dozens. Over ten completed their studies and took the civil service exam. Five or six await the final examination after passing the preliminary. Among those who passed were Cho Wei of Haysan and Yu Hojin of Koryŏng—both cultivated by our magistrate's instruction, their eloquent prose and forceful brushwork now renowned throughout the southern provinces.

    Kyŏngch'un marveled, wondering how a naturally barren region could be so transformed. One day when the magistrate came with Yu Hojin, Kyŏngch'un went to receive him. Observing his countenance, he saw a composed and taciturn bearing; hearing his speech, it was clear yet hesitant. Then Kyŏngch'un knew he was no ordinary man, and recognized the magistrate's immense power to educate. They formed a deep friendship, and in frequent intercourse, Kyŏngch'un observed that his learning was profound and vast, his writings vigorous and rich—unburdened by petty affairs, he possessed a noble disregard for worldly glory and a reverence for virtue.

    Shortly after, when Yu received appointment to the capital, he came to take leave. Kyŏngch'un composed a poem and sent it with a recommendation to Sŏ Kangjung at the Four Excellences Pavilion, saying: "The old master of the Four Excellences now receives scholars; one glance will fix your name in his memory." Kyŏngch'un also came to the capital, and after the mourning period ended, again took position in the Royal Lecture Hall. Yu's reputation had already spread throughout the capital—he was recognized as a master of letters. The king granted him special leave to study, intending to employ him greatly. Before a year passed, he was appointed Doctor of the Hongmun Hall, where all his colleagues acknowledged him as a man of great capacity. Soon after, he was promoted to Vice Editor-in-Chief. Yet Yu's parents remained in distant Hamyang, hundreds of li away. Each spring and autumn, when he requested leave to visit them, the king invariably granted it and provided relay horses. One day he submitted his petition to return and serve his aging parents. The king, moved by his filial resolve, granted permission and ordered the Ministry of Personnel to find him a nearby magistracy. How glorious!

    Upon his departure, he asked me to write this account. I reflect on the words of Confucius: "To establish oneself in virtue, to bring honor to one's name, and thereby to illuminate one's parents—this is the beginning of filial piety." Every man with the opportunity should serve a worthy ruler, bring about good governance, become renowned as a minister, enjoy abundant stipends, feast at grand tables, and in life provide for his parents abundantly, in death fulfill all proper rites. This is what all men desire.

    Yet some serve far from home, unable to attend their parents; they climb mountains with an aching heart, gaze at clouds in sorrow. To follow personal inclination leaves no opportunity for filial glory; to pursue office neglects the duty of intimate care. What then is to be done? The ancients said: "The days of serving one's lord are many; the days of serving one's parents are few." With such precious, fleeting time, and parents whose need is urgent and whose days grow short, a filial son must weigh carefully what is truly essential.

    Yu, though positioned to rise high, hesitated not. He set down his official robes and returned south—truly one who understands the hierarchy of duty. When he arrives, persimmons and chestnuts will hang heavy on the hills, rice will overflow the fields, silver fish will be at their finest, white grain fragrant and fresh. He will gather seasonal delicacies, pour fragrant wine, arrange varied delicacies, and present them to his parents on the high platform. With ruddy cheeks and white hair still robust and healthy, they will eat well. He will retire and share the remainder with his children, day after day, peacefully completing the year. What joy could compare with this? Not all the treasures and honors of the empire could tempt him to exchange this for that. Those who cling to distant posts, forgetting their aging parents, clinging to petty office—do they not feel ashamed? Their foreheads must sweat with regret.

    Ah, how many who enjoy wealth and fame seem outwardly free from sorrow, yet harbor within them the sorrow of "the bitter gourd vine," carrying perpetual grief that reaches to heaven? Yu shall find true peace of heart. When we speak of another's virtue, we trace it to its source to illuminate its origin. In recounting Yu's rise and his wisdom to withdraw, I would honor the magistrate Kim, whose instruction wrought this transformation. Yet also, may the youth of these mountains be moved by his example to strengthen their own resolve. Go forth, Yu, and know the blessing that awaits you.
